= notes on first reading =
=== Alternative theories ===
===== received view =====
dreams are (or at least involve) experiences that occur during sleep
There are experiences _there then_ that may be forgotten upon waking or soon
afterwards.
===== dennett's fantasy projection of received view =====
there are two processes occurring during sleep when one is dreaming.
1) presentation: neural events that represent the events in the dream. (which
   presumably give rise to experiences)
2) A process of recording those events into memory.

later (fp. 7) a third process is added:
3) composition(/generation?) of the dream experiences
===== Malcolm's view =====
If I call it, its a strike! <br>
People have <q>authority</q> over their dream contents. A more than somewhat
verificationist view seemingly reminiscent of Wittgenstein's account. (and hence
wrong) Hence there is nothing occurring when you are asleep (otherwise you could
be wrong about it).
===== production upon waking =====
This view is invented purely to solve the [[#precognition problem]].
    dreams are composed and presented _very fast_ in the interval between bang,
    bump, or buzz and full consciousness, with some short delay system
    postponing the full "perception" of the noise in the dream until the
    presentation of the narrative is ready for it.
===== cassette theory =====
This is also introduced to solve the [[#precognition problem]]
    perhaps there is a "library" in the brain of undreamed dreams with various
    indexed endings, and the bang or bump or buzz has the effect of retrieving
    an appropriate dream and inserting it, cassette-like, in the memory
    mechanism.

On the cassette view we never dream our dream at all, only spuriously
<q>recall</q> them upon waking. The presentation (process (1) above) is ommitted
altogether. Various version of the cassette theory some of these dream cassettes
might be innate, some might be composed at various times by some unconscious
process.

===== REM composition cassette theory =====
<q>On this theory dream memories are produced just the way the received theory says
they are, except for one crucial thing: the process of dream-memory
production is entirely unconscious, involves no awareness or experiencing at
all.</q>
The composition stage occurs when, according to the received view, the
presentation process is thought to occur (basically during REM sleep).

The (sole?) superiority of this view is that it accounts for the
[[#precognition problem]]

dennett's view
 
 == evidence ==
*eye movements*: gross features of REM eye movements sometimes match the content. Looking left
and right - later reported dreaming of watching a tennis match. Looking up and
down - later reported dreaming of throwing basketballs.
 
*precognition problem*: this is the key bit of evidence to explain, and the
chief motivation for the dreams dont occur while sleeping but may occur upon
waking (or perhaps the <q>recollection</q> is when you are doing the dream
activity).

An alarm clock, sudden noise, drip of water, is incorporated into a dream at its
climax and the dreamer wakes up to find that it is real. How could that
(lengthy?) dream have made up all that if I were experiencing it over the time
it <q>seemd to take</q> and then coincide with that waking-up real world
stimulus/event.
    If the terminal events in these dreams are strongly prepared for by the
    narrative, if they do not consist of radically juxtaposed turns in the
    narrative (for example, the goat turns into a telephone and starts ringing),
    then the composition process must have been directed by something having
    "knowledge" of the future.<br>
    (fp. 9)

===== my own dream =====
Twice now I have had a dream when I am interacting with an electronic device.
Once it was my phone, once it was something else I cannot now recall. But it was
making a noise (not unpleasant or loud merely annoying) and I turned it off in
the normal way. It failed, repeatedly try to turn off the device and become
frustrated at its lack of response. I go into <q>tech problem solving mode</q>
and seem to try various methods of turning off the device, trying to trouble
shoot why the device is not responding. It <q>seems like</q> a very extended
process. In one dream I think I gave up, in the other I just kept trying, in
both I woke up to find I had left my phone playing some extended
podcast/whatever without a sleep timer and it was annoying me.

Not precognitive, indeed in some ways anti-precognitive. Seems to
circumstantially support the received view.
 
=== possible future evidence ===
a successful theory would enable us to predict what someone reports as the
content of their dreams from observation of their physiology during their sleep.

scientists might correct someones dream recollection - <q>No you didnt dream
