=== responses to discovering an alternative theory was true ===
Suppose we dicovered that the [[#cassette theory]] or the
[[#production upon waking]] theory was true. Then it would turn out that wew had
been under an illusion that we were dreaming while we slept. Malcolm views this
as senseless (it breaks dreamers authority, for Wittgenstein breaks a criterion
for having had a dream viz., saying that you did).

This is the standard [[solid_objects]] case


== solutions to precognitive dreams ==


===== my view =====
The nonlinguistic representation system is both a expectation generating system
(i.e. a simulator/prediction generator) it is also the recollection system or at
least a key part of it (this is why we have <q>semantic</q> search/recollection
which is the alchemists stone of search engines).

This fits beautifully with at least the following element of Dennett's view:
    We interpret, extrapolate, revise; it sometimes seems that we "relive" the
    incidents and draw conclusions from this reliving-conclusions that are then
    expressed in what we actually compose then and there as our recollections.<br>
    (fp. 5)
He then asks:
    (cont:)It is not easy to analyze what must be going on when this happens.
    What is the raw material, the evidence, the basis for these reconstructions
    we call recollections?
One suggestion - often but no always the initial prompt will be a sentence.
(Better saved by effective digitisation). This may trigger a running of the
simulation with the grossest features in place. Then further
attentional/computation resources are invested in fleshing out the simulation.
Other times it may be something similar that triggers recollection. Recollection
is not sharply distinguished from imagination. At other times one may try to
reverse engineer. The device of <q>working out</q> that someone/something/some
detail had to be there. <q>Right, it was my first coffee of the day, and I had
got to work late</q> and then using that to <q>seed</q> the neural simulation is
often effective.

the traces are going to be stored in defusable connections/tendencies in the
neural simulation component/components. These slight adjustments in the
expectational generation connections will outlast the memory - they will become
too diffuse to trigger a <q>resimulation</q> of the event, and at that point we
call it forgotten.

So a number of features one might expect:
There is no sharp line between recollection and invention.
	- at the time of recollection striving to <q>remember</q> may result in the
	  construction of new details of the dream that were not experienced (or at
	  least neurally represented) during REM sleep
During the dream details will be invented as one pays attention to them.
	- e.g. when one looks at a book one will be able to read it and it will
	  have had text in it <q>all along</q> (it was not a blank book in which
	  writing suddenly appeared) but there was no neural representation of that
	  text before one looks.
	- In a dream one looks up from the table/whatever was occupying one's
	  attention and suddenly <q>recognises</q> your great aunt/school
	  friend/whomever. In a sense its utterly implausible that they could have
	  sat down without your recognising them. The sequence goes as follows: you
	  dream you are in a cafe, what do you do at a cafe? look out the window and
	  drink coffee while there are people around. Brain runs low level
	  undetailed simulation of people around you, and detailed simulation of
	  what you are attending to - the scene outside the window and the smell of
	  coffee. Your attention wanders to your surroundings in the cafe - there
	  are people here - which people - ah simulation summons up 
	- a person simulation in order to fulfill your previous belief that there
	  are people here, but now you are attending to it it has to be a particular
	  person - voila: your aunt.

